article.description:
Because Antawn Jamison criticized his passing earlier in the
week, Gilbert Arenas decided to avoidshooting in the first 3 1/2 quarters of the Golden State Warriors' 111-107 victory over the New York Knicks.
article.headline: Arenas avoids shooting until fourth, when he takes over
article.linkText: Arenas plays games with everyone, including Knicks
article.story:
OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) -- Only a player with Gilbert Arenas' talent could get away with something so crazy -- and only a player with Arenas' confidence would be crazy enough to try it. Because Antawn Jamison criticized his passing earlier in the week -- and just because he's a bit odd -- Arenas decided to avoid shooting in the first 3 1/2 quarters of the Golden State Warriors' 111-107 victory over the New York Knicks on Friday night. When the Warriors fell nine points behind the Knicks in the final minutes, Arenas finally decided to end his experiment -- and he scored 14 points as the Warriors made a stirring fourth-quarter rally to snap their three-game losing streak. It was a bizarre sight in an otherwise superbly played game: Arenas, the Warriors' second-leading scorer and one of the NBA's emerging stars this season, consciously passing up all but one shot, which he missed, and declining to attack the hoop. "It was just something I came up with myself,'' Arenas said. "You've got to have a lot of (guts) to pull something off like that -- not score for 3 1/2 quarters and then try to take over the game. "I've been hot for the last three weeks, though. No matter how many times I shoot in a game, I'm still going to be on fire.'' Jamison, who said he wasn't getting enough good shots after going scoreless in Golden State's loss at Portland on Wednesday night, scored 31 points and hit the go-ahead shot with 55 seconds left. Troy Murphy had 17 points and 14 rebounds as the Warriors beat the Knicks in Oakland for the first time since Nov. 17, 1994. Golden State got 32 offensive rebounds -- the highest total in the NBA this season, and one shy of the record for a Knicks opponent. The Warriors outrebounded New York 62-39, but the Knicks hit enough outside jumpers to nearly steal the win. Until Arenas decided to help out, that is. "We had nobody on the floor that could guard him,'' New York coach Don Chaney said. "I've watched tape after tape, and he just takes over games. He has a great, quick first step, and he can step back and hit the 3. I told our guys, 'This is the guy that takes over.''' Warriors coach Eric Musselman didn't hear about Arenas' plan until after the game. In the final minutes, however, Musselman screamed at his point guard to start scoring -- and so he did. "Gilbert did a great job distributing the ball,'' Musselman said while shaking his head in bewilderment. "I would have to say he played just about a perfect floor game -- but we won't be disappointed if he'd like to shoot a little more.'' Kurt Thomas scored 32 points for the Knicks -- one shy of his career high -- in a meeting of two teams still nursing unlikely playoff hopes. New York lost its third straight after winning the first two games on a six-game West Coast road swing. The Knicks lost to the Warriors for the second time in nine days, following Golden State's 113-107 win at Madison Square Garden last week. "This was probably the worst loss of the trip so far, because of the nature of the game, how close it was, and knowing that we were right there,'' Sprewell said. "This is the one we're most disappointed with thus far.'' New York had two chances to tie in the final seconds, but Howard Eisley and Thomas couldn't get clean 3-point shots, with Arenas slapping the ball out of Eisley's hands as he went up. New York led 96-87 before the Warriors scored 10 straight points in 2 minutes, capped by Arenas' driving dunk with 4:22 left. Golden State went up by five, but Thomas' jumper with 1:24 left put New York up 104-103. After Jamison hit one of his trademark leaners from 10 feet, the Knicks couldn't score from inside. After dribbling down the clock, Arenas drove around Sprewell for a layup with 17.9 seconds left. Allan Houston hit a quick jumper, but Jamison sneaked behind New York's defense for a dunk off Murphy's long inbounds pass with 11.8 seconds left. "I thought we had a nice defensive game, even though they scored a lot of points,'' Jamison said. "We'd rather have Kurt Thomas shoot a lot of shots than Spree and Houston.'' Adonal Foyle matched his career high with nine blocked shots for the Warriors, and the Knicks countered Golden State's size with outside scoring. Houston had 17 points, while Shandon Anderson had a season-high 18. Sprewell, booed every time he touched the ball by his former home fans, had nine points and 10 assists.

Game notes
Golden State swept the season series from New York for the first time since 1990-91. ... Earl Boykins went 1-for-8 from the field for Golden State. ... Before the game, New York put Ward on the injured list and activated rookie Frank Williams, who had missed the previous 39 games with a heel injury. On his first trip down the court in the second quarter, Williams drove to the hoop and had his shot swatted into the crowd by Erick Dampier.
